b"-- Over the long term, $ASAN's success will turn on its ability to grow its customers while dialing back the spend. If it can do that and maintain its 87% gross margin, there's  plenty of room for this  $4.6B market cap company to run."

b'-- Furthering the concern is that $ASAN competes in a crowded market that includes $GOOGL, $MSFT, $SMAR, and $TEAM.\n\n-- In the near term, $ASAN will likely have to maintain its high spend to remain competitive, which it can do with $424M of cash and short-term investments.'

b"-- The ability of $ASAN's platform to increase productivity has led to a strong international customer base, with 89K customers in 190 countries and 42% of revenue coming from outside of the US.\n\n-- $ASAN also has an impressive 87% gross margin."

b"-- $ASAN's customers have overwhelmingly provided positive feedback: 83% say its improve job performance, 77% say it reduce time waste, and 74% say it helps complete tasks faster.\n\n-- Of $ASAN's top 100 customers, the overwhelming majority started with the free offering."

b"-- This freemium model creates flywheel opportunities: a team within a company begins using $ASAN's platform, creating an opening for $ASAN to sell its software across the enterprise using the first team's positive experience as evidence of the product's value."

b'-- $ASAN uses freemium and land and expand strategies to acquire and grow customer relationships.\n\n-- It offers free basic software and three levels of paid subscription: Premium ($10 per year per user), Business ($24 per year per user), and Enterprise (custom price plan).'

b"-- To solve this problem, $ASAN's platform captures, organizes, and presents productivity data points, including units of work (e.g. tasks or projects), employees involved, and progress updates.  \n\n-- It allows team members to check on project's status without calls or emails. https://t.co/xLTKLsU7vP"
